snippet.textDisplay: Now, Bloomberg may be racist, and I'm no supporter of his, nor am I a supporter of stop and frisk. However, his statement in that clip isn't racist. He didn't say "minorities are bad and cause crime", he said "we put cops in high crime neighborhoods, which tend to be high-minority neighborhoods.". He's saying that it is a statistical consequence, not that he's targeting minorities. Again, I'm not saying anything about the accuracy of that statement because I don't know if that's true or not, but that statement itself is not racist. It's just like if you said you were going to fight money crimes harder and said "we're arresting a lot of white people because we're targeting high-income neighborhoods, which tend to have more money crime, which tend to be white-majority neighborhoods.". That wouldn't be a racist statement against white people, and it isn't saying "we're targeting white people".

I really liked Birds of Prey. It had really good ups and just a tad cringe in a certain scene with the special effects, as well as some a little sub par script occasionally, specifically with the restaurant owner, but other than that I thought it was good as far as DC movies go. Margot honestly owns Harley Quinn, she does such a fantastic job. I had no problem with the feminism in the movie, compared to say "redoing the ghost busters with an all female cast just because its an all female cast," as some of the other comments mention the movie was very self aware and that really helped with the social commentary aspect. I do not know a lot about the extended DC universe and from other comments apparently this is an inaccurate telling as far as DC lore goes, and that's probably why people are hesitant to see it. As far as making Harley less sexy, I think that's a bit dramatic . Harley and the gang are still very attractive (not that it should be why you're going to see the movie in the first place?) and I think just makes it easier to focus on the fact that Margot is killing it as Harley Quinn.


Id give it on a true scale close to a 7/10, good movie with some deadpool kinda vibes at times.

snippet.textDisplay:
I don't yet know where I stand on the stop and frisk situation.
But I wonder.. Should we not use statistics when making these decisions?

If one particular group, area, or demographic are statisticly more likely to commit a crime, then shouldn't we put more effort towards mitigating crime in those groups/areas/demographics?

Surely, our main efforts should be in tackling why the statistics are as they are. I imagine this can be done with education and economic policies. But while the data shows a particular statistic, I don't see it to be racist at all the implement those mitigation.

Like anything of importance, there's no simple solution. But I feel it's dangerous to start labeling data as racist.
snippet.textOriginal:
I don't yet know where I stand on the stop and frisk situation.
But I wonder.. Should we not use statistics when making these decisions?

If one particular group, area, or demographic are statisticly more likely to commit a crime, then shouldn't we put more effort towards mitigating crime in those groups/areas/demographics?

Surely, our main efforts should be in tackling why the statistics are as they are. I imagine this can be done with education and economic policies. But while the data shows a particular statistic, I don't see it to be racist at all the implement those mitigation.

Like anything of importance, there's no simple solution. But I feel it's dangerous to start labeling data as racist.
